<TITLE> Renowned sportswoman Salma Rafique passes away </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 9 (bdnews24.com)Sports organiser, former athlete and executive editor of fortnightly Krira Jagat Salma Rafique died in Dhaka on Saturday morning at the age of 57. She had been suffering from cancer for the last one year. Salma, wife of the chief feature writer of information ministry late Gazi Rafiqul Islam, left behind a daughter and a host of well-wishers. She was buried at the Mirpur martyred intellectuals graveyard after a namaz-e-janaza was held at SOS Shishu Palli Mosque in Shaymoli in the capital. She joined Krira Jagat in 1977 after working at Daily Samaj, Daily Azad and weekly Kishor Bangla. Salma was engaged in sports from her childhood and took part in shot-put, discus throw and hurdles for the then East Pakistan, Pakistan Olympic, National Athletics, inter-university competition, Azad Sporting Cub, Dhaka University and DU Rokeya Hall. She represented Bangladesh in 'the All-India Rural Games' in volleyball, kabaddi, kho kho in 1973. She was also a member of first national women's volleyball and Kabaddi teams. Salma played a role as an executive member of National Women's Sports Council as well as Bangladesh Kabaddi Federation, joint-secretaries of Dhaka Metropolis Sports Association and Bangladesh Women's Hockey Association. State Minister for Youth and Sports Ahad Ali Sarker, president of Bangladesh Olympic Association and the high officials of different National Federations expressed their shock at the news of Salma's death and prayed for the departed soul. bd
